{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9be93e5d-a252-4fc8-a025-469c77caed00","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues I found:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Recursive wildcard glob (line 9, `EvalHeavy.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` forces MSBuild to enumerate the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. This is the most expensive pattern here — cost grows with every file added to the repo.\n\n### 2. File I/O property function (line 13, `EvalHeavy.csproj`)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` during **evaluation** (not build) blocks the MSBuild evaluator on disk I/O. Property functions that read files are strongly discouraged — use a target-phase `ReadLinesFromFile` task instead.\n\n### 3. Deeply chained imports (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import is parsed and evaluated sequentially. While 3 levels is modest, the chain is unnecessary — the props only set one property each and could be flattened into a single file.\n\n### Summary\n\n| Issue | Impact | Fix |\n|---|---|---|\n| `**\\*.*` glob | High — full tree walk every evaluation | Narrow the glob to specific extensions/dirs |\n| `File::ReadAllText` in property | Medium — synchronous I/O during eval | Move to a target using `ReadLinesFromFile` |\n| 3-deep import chain | Low–Medium — serial parse overhead | Flatten into one `.props` file |\n\nThe recursive glob and the file-read property function are the two patterns that will hurt most as the project scales.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"31f2e763-fea7-4368-b904-acbcd6895c76","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project.\n\nI've found several patterns that cause slow project evaluation:\n\n1. **Deep import chain** (level1.props → level2.props → level3.props): 3-deep nesting of imports increases evaluation time as MSBuild must parse and evaluate each file sequentially.\n\n2. **Recursive wildcard glob** (`**\\*.*`): The `AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\"` pattern forces MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree during evaluation. This is expensive, especially as the project grows.\n\n3. **File I/O during evaluation** (`$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))`): Property functions that perform file I/O during evaluation are expensive. This reads the entire file content into a property at evaluation time.\n\n\n4. **Overly broad glob with exclusions**: Using `Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\"` matches everything first then filters it out, which is inefficient compared to a more targeted pattern from the start.","outputTokens":714,"requestId":"7823:1909B6:1F6A257:23D9A62:69F55249"},"id":"ac0bb774-2b17-4d85-bbee-c8029c8b374a","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:24:41.789Z","parentId":"f4924385-9212-473f-a25a-fffb11273ed0"}
